 seated position upon ones shoulders especially in celebration or victory.";i:2;s:38:"No its not transitive in that context.";i:3;s:69:"Chair is part of a prepositional clause that indicates where he sits.";i:4;s:162:"You can check this link from Oxford Learners Dictionary with multiple examples of both the transitive and the intransitive modes but let me quote the definitions.";i:5;s:51:"Has broken verb transitive verb of the noun clause.";i:6;s:62:"The chair object of the verb has broken the chair noun phrase.";i:7;s:55:"In sum there are two transitive verbs in this sentence.";i:8;s:20:"Know and has broken.";i:9;s:28:"The chair was sat on by her.";i:10;s:137:"Transitive passive If you want to say that sat on is a transitive verb you need to say it is transitive in the active and in the passive.";i:11;s:37:"Voice has no bearing on transitivity.";i:12;s:73:"The addition of an agent by-phrase has no bearing on transitivity either.";i:13;s:36:"Transitive verb To place in a chair.";i:14;s:66:"Transitive verb engraving To carry publicly in a chair in triumph.";i:15;s:70:"Transitive verb To function as chairperson of a meeting committee etc.";i:16;s:89:"Transitive verb If you chair a meeting or a committee you are the person in charge of it.";i:17;s:48:"He was about to chair a meeting in Venice of EU.";i:18;s:36:"Cochair or co-chair transitive verb.";i:19;s:101:"A new antidrug commission cochaired by a corporate leader and a high-ranking administration official.";i:20;s:38:"On the edge of your seat chair phrase.";i:21;s:82:"Chair definition is - a seat typically having four legs and a back for one person.";i:22;s:31:"How to use chair in a sentence.";i:23;s:30:"Chair can be a noun or a verb.";i:24;s:96:"He wanted to chair the committee Verb form She wanted a new chair for the living room Noun form.";i:25;s:74:"A transitive verb is a verb that requires an object to receive the action.";i:26;s:66:"The speaker discussed different marketing strategies in the video.";i:27;s:35:"The speaker discussed in the video.";i:28;s:67:"The verb discuss requires an object different marketing strategies.";i:29;s:52:"It is necessary to state what the speaker discussed.";i:30;s:53:"A transitive verb is one that is used with an object.";i:31;s:103:"A noun phrase or pronoun that refers to the person or thing that is affected by the action of the verb.";i:32;s:78:"In the following sentences admire maintain face and love are transitive verbs.";i:33;s:22:"I admire your courage.";i:34;s:36:"We need to maintain product quality.";i:35;s:54:"Panthers climb trees with their short and strong legs.";i:36;s:15:"Object trees 9.";i:37;s:21:"She sat on the chair.";i:38;s:20:"Sat intransitive 10.";i:39;s:32:"They took the child to hospital.";i:40;s:20:"Object the child 11.";i:41;s:22:"Mother laid the table.";i:42;s:20:"Object the table 12.";i:43;s:13:"I want a job.";i:44;s:13:"Object a job.";i:45;s:28:"The chair was sat on by her.";i:46;s:75:"That kind of passive is called by many linguists the prepositional passive.";i:47;s:130:"In the active-voice sentence you have the intransitive verb sit in the past tense modified by a prepositional phrase on the chair.";i:48;s:44:"In the passive-voice sentence the object of.";i:49;s:25:"Short for electric chair.";i:50;s:112:"They fear this peaceful drug dealer and because of this fear they want him to die by the chair of electrocution.";i:51;s:100:"At the trial the man is sent down for murder and seeing as its Texas hes sent to the electric chair.";i:52;s:26:"What are transitive verbs.";i:53;s:77:"Transitive verbs are action verbs that have an object to receive that action.";i:54;s:87:"In the first sentence above the direct object ball received the action of the verb hit.";i:55;s:39:"Some more examples of transitive verbs.";i:56;s:19:"I rode the bicycle.";i:57;s:18:"I moved the chair.";i:58;s:28:"What are intransitive verbs.";i:59;s:44:"Eg The little girl sat quietly in the chair.";i:60;s:39:"Margaret walked slowly down the street.";i:61;s:38:"Sat and walked are intransitive verbs.";i:62;s:67:"They do not have a direct object to complete or receive the action.";i:63;s:78:"Some verbs can be either transitive or intransitive depending on how they are.";i:64;s:50:"As you may know transitive verbs act on an object.";i:65;s:100:"For example in the sentence he played the piano the verb played corresponds to the object the piano.";i:66;s:75:"But for intransitive verbs these types of verbs dont relate to any objects.";i:67;s:101:"For example in the sentence she slept all day the verb slept doesnt coincide with any type of object.";i:68;s:62:"So lets put these concepts into practice with this transitive.";i:69;s:92:"Chair VERB tʃɛə If you chair a meeting or a committee you are the person in charge of it.";i:70;s:53:"He was about to chair a meeting of foreign ministers.";i:71;s:53:"A transitive verb is one that is used with an object.";i:72;s:103:"A noun phrase or pronoun that refers to the person or thing that is affected by the action of the verb.";i:73;s:78:"In the following sentences admire maintain face and love are transitive verbs.";i:74;s:22:"I admire your courage.";i:75;s:36:"We need to maintain product quality.";i:76;s:25:"I couldnt face him today.";i:77;s:34:"A transitive verb takes an object.";i:78;s:45:"An intransitive verb does not have an object.";i:79;s:32:"A class usually has 30 students.";i:80;s:31:"She always carries an umbrella.";i:81;s:38:"I read an interesting story yesterday.";i:82;s:22:"The dog barked loudly.";i:83;s:31:"The child was sleeping soundly.";i:84;s:76:"He sits can be followed by a prepositional phrase such as on a wooden chair.";i:85;s:140:"But using a noun immediately after the verb eg He sits a wooden chair would make an incorrect sentence because the verb cant take an object.";i:86;s:105:"However many verbs can be both transitive or intransitive depending on what follows them in the sentence.";i:87;s:136:"This page will help you identify transitive and intransitive verbs and phrasal verbsA transitive verb is a verb that can have an object.";i:88;s:126:"For example the verb kickSandra kicked the ballsubjectverbobjectThe object of the verb kick in the above sentence is the ball.";i:89;s:49:"Transitive verbs like kick are common in English.";i:90;s:24:"Used as Transitive Verb.";i:91;s:26:"Used as Intransitive Verb.";i:92;s:30:"The boys are flying the kites.";i:93;s:32:"The birds are flying in the air.";i:94;s:32:"My friend is running a tutorial.";i:95;s:38:"They ran fast on seeing the principal.";i:96;s:27:"Have you washed your hands.";i:97;s:30:"I washed dressed and went out.";i:98;s:25:"She wrote a letter to me.";i:99;s:26:"She cannot read and write.";i:100;s:34:"The teacher started a new chapter.";}}